  <h2>Why Disease Prevention Matters</h2>
  <p>
    Disease outbreaks are the single greatest threat to profitable shrimp farming. A single WSSV outbreak can destroy an entire harvest in days, costing tens of thousands of dollars. The good news? Most diseases can be prevented with proper management practices and the right products.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide covers the most common shrimp diseases, their causes, and proven prevention strategies that successful farms use to protect their stock.
  </p>

  <h2>Common Shrimp Diseases</h2>

  <h3>White Spot Syndrome Virus (WSSV)</h3>
  <p>
    WSSV is the most devastating shrimp virus worldwide. It causes rapid mortality — often within 3-10 days of first signs. Infected shrimp develop white spots on their shell and become lethargic.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Transmission:</strong> Contact with infected shrimp, contaminated water, or vectors like crabs</li>
    <li><strong>Speed:</strong> Can cause 100% mortality within days</li>
    <li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Biosecurity, certified SPF seed, immune boosters</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Early Mortality Syndrome (EMS)</h3>
  <p>
    EMS, also known as Acute Hepatopancreatic Necrosis Disease (AHPND), attacks the hepatopancreas, causing massive die-offs in the first 30 days of culture.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Transmission:</strong> Likely through contaminated feed and water</li>
    <li><strong>Speed:</strong> Kills within 20-30 days of stocking</li>
    <li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Pond preparation, probiotics, water quality management</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Vibrio Infections</h3>
  <p>
    Vibrio bacteria cause a range of problems from slow growth to sudden death. V. parahaemolyticus and V. harveyi are the most common pathogenic species.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Transmission:</strong> Naturally present in water, proliferates under stress</li>
    <li><strong>Speed:</strong> Can cause mortality within days under stress conditions</li>
    <li><strong>Prevention:</strong> Water quality management, immune support, targeted antimicrobials</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The 5 Pillars of Disease Prevention</h2>

  <h3>1. Pond Preparation</h3>
  <p>
    Proper pond preparation is your first line of defense. A clean, well-prepared pond eliminates many pathogens before stocking begins. Key steps include complete draining, drying, liming, and biological preparation.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Quality Seed Selection</h3>
  <p>
    Always source SPF (Specific Pathogen Free) post-larvae from certified hatcheries. The quality of your seed stock determines your disease risk for the entire grow-out cycle.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Water Quality Management</h3>
  <p>
    Stable water quality is critical. Daily monitoring of ammonia, nitrite, pH, dissolved oxygen, and alkalinity helps you catch problems before they become crises. Invest in reliable testing equipment.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Immune System Support</h3>
  <p>
    Healthy shrimp with strong immune systems resist disease better. Regular use of immune stimulants like Immuno-Boost Pro builds natural resistance against pathogens.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Biosecurity Measures</h3>
  <p>
    Control access to your farm. Disinfect equipment, restrict visitor access, and maintain separate tools for each pond. These simple steps prevent pathogen introduction.
  </p>

  <h2>Building Your Prevention Program</h2>
  <p>
    The most successful shrimp farms don't wait for disease — they prevent it. Here's a simple timeline you can follow:
  </p>

  <h3>Week -2: Pond Preparation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Drain and dry pond completely</li>
    <li>Apply Soil Renew to break down organic matter</li>
    <li>Apply lime for pH stabilization</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Week -1: Biological Setup</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Apply Pond Prep Elite to establish beneficial bacteria</li>
    <li>Fill pond and begin aeration</li>
    <li>Test water parameters daily</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Day 0: Stocking</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Verify all water parameters are within range</li>
    <li>Apply Stress-Away Plus to reduce handling stress</li>
    <li>Stock certified SPF post-larvae</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Week 1-2: Early Protection</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Begin feeding Immuno-Boost Pro with feed</li>
    <li>Monitor water quality twice daily</li>
    <li>Watch for signs of stress or disease</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to Act Fast</h2>
  <p>
    Even with the best prevention, problems can arise. Know these warning signs:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Sudden drop in feed consumption</li>
    <li>Unusual swimming patterns (surface swimming, erratic movement)</li>
    <li>White spots on shell (possible WSSV)</li>
    <li>Soft shell or loose exoskeleton</li>
    <li>Mass mortality without obvious cause</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you observe these signs, immediately test water quality, reduce feeding, and contact your technical support team. Early intervention can save your harvest.
  </p>

  <h2>Conclusion</h2>
  <p>
    Disease prevention is not optional in shrimp farming — it's essential. By following these five pillars and maintaining vigilant monitoring, you can dramatically reduce your risk of disease outbreaks and improve your farm's profitability.
  </p>
